  abstract = {Stone tool-making is an ancient and prototypically human skill
              characterized by multiple levels of intentional organization. In a
              formal sense, it displays surprising similarities to the
              multi-level organization of human language. Recent functional brain
              imaging studies of stone tool-making similarly demonstrate overlap
              with neural circuits involved in language processing. These
              observations are consistent with the hypothesis that language and
              tool-making share key requirements for the construction of
              hierarchically structured action sequences and evolved together in
              a mutually reinforcing way.},
